\subsection{Observations}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \emph{Diminishing Returns:} Beyond 8 threads, overhead from locking and task setup reduces marginal gains.
  \item \emph{Load Balance:} Monte Carlo tasks evenly distribute work, while decision‐tree branches may vary in computational weight.
  \item \emph{Amdahl’s Law:} Non‐parallelizable portions (e.g., state setup) limit maximal speedup.
\end{itemize}

\section{How to Run the Code}

\subsection{Prerequisites}
\begin{itemize}
  \item A C++ compiler supporting C++20.
  \item CMake (minimum version 3.20).
  \item OpenMP support in your compiler.
  \item Access to the Stampede3 supercomputer.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Steps to Build and Run}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Log in to Stampede3 and navigate to your project directory:
  \begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
  ssh <your_username>@stampede3.tacc.utexas.edu
  cd ~/COE379L/final_project
  \end{lstlisting}

  \item Create a build directory and configure the build:
  \begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
  mkdir build
  cd build
  cmake -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release ..
  \end{lstlisting}

  \item Compile the code using multiple threads:
  \begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
  make -j
  \end{lstlisting}

  \item Set the number of OpenMP threads and run the program:
  \begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
  export OMP_NUM_THREADS=8
  ./final_project 3 10000
  \end{lstlisting}
  Here, `3` is the decision tree depth, and `10000` is the number of Monte Carlo simulations.

\subsection{Input Files}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \texttt{Cards.txt}: Contains the Pokémon card database.
  \item \texttt{deck.txt}: Specifies the player's 20-card deck.
  \item \texttt{metaDecks.txt}: Contains predefined meta-decks for opponent estimation.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Gameplay Instructions}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Prepare your deck in \texttt{deck.txt} and ensure all cards are defined in \texttt{Cards.txt}.
  \item Run the program and follow the prompts to:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Load your deck.
    \item View your starting hand.
    \item Set up the initial board state.
  \end{itemize}
  \item Input game state updates after each round to receive probabilistic insights and recommendations.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Conclusion}
Parallelizing Pokémon TCG simulations with OpenMP delivers substantial performance improvements, enabling deeper strategic evaluations in practical time. Running the program on Stampede3 demonstrates the scalability of the approach, with significant speedups observed for Monte Carlo simulations and decision tree evaluations. Future work could integrate MPI for multi‐node scaling, implement dynamic load balancing for tree exploration, and optimize memory locality to further reduce overhead.

